messages.text: SafeHaven chat. 02/09/17. 3:12 AM.
patientzero is connected.
Dr. Took, uh, I know you won't see this for a while, I guess.
I'm sorry for the things I said when we last spoke.
I'm getting more paranoid about my brother.
Like, he was sitting in the kitchen earlier—he came to my house to eat.
And he was staring at the wall with dull eyes and all that, and then out of nowhere he threw a beer bottle at the wall.
I thought I heard a crunch when it broke—like the lady's body did when—well, you know.
I can't believe I've told you all of this.
I looked in the mirror this morning and didn't recognize myself—my own reflection.
I looked like a stranger I'd never seen before, except in a distant dream.
I've been drinking since.
I think I need to go to the field.
She's still there, lying in the tall grasses beside the road.
No one found her yet, I don't think.
I need to bury her.
patientzero is disconnected.
SafeHaven chat 02/09/17 6:49 AM.
patientzero is connected.
I went to the field.
I couldn't bury her.
I thought I'd be able to but—good God, it's been three months.
I took a shovel but she's just a puddle of rotted flesh and flies.
Her bones are still in there but I couldn't get any closer without being sick.
I could see her empty eye sockets looking at me.
I went to the bathroom a few minutes ago to get some cold water on my face.
I looked in the mirror and saw her empty eye sockets where mine should be.
I had no eyes.
Oh, God.
I drove drunk again.
patientzero is disconnected.
SafeHaven chat. 02/09/17. 1:07 PM.
Dr. Took is connected.
patientzero is connected.
I received your messages just now, patientzero, and I am very concerned about you. Can you tell me more about what's been going on since we last spoke?
I quit my job.
I'm sorry to hear that. Where had you been working?
At the gas station.
I was scheduled to work this morning but I went to the river instead.
How come?
I threw the shovel in. I was afraid to keep it around here.
I see. I'm worried about your current mental state. I think you may need to seek out medical advice, patientzero.
Why? You're a doctor.
I'm a psychologist. I don't have a medical license and I can't prescribe medication.
You think I need pills?
I think you need to be evaluated by a doctor in person.
Yeah, right. So they can sic the cops on me.
How did you feel when you went to the field?
Uh, I don't know. In a trance, I guess.
Why did you choose to go there?
I heard her crying.
Who?
You know—the lady.
She sounded like she was in a deep cave or something. Her voice echoed.
Did she say anything to you?
No, not to me.
She cried to herself.
She said she couldn't forget how it felt—she kept saying "crunch, crunch, crunch."
Like her bones were cracking under the tires all over again.
And at the field?
I saw her—what was left of her—and couldn't look. I went to the river to get rid of the shovel.
That's it.
Did you go home after that?
Yeah, but I still couldn't sleep.
Why not?
I saw my brother's eyes in the window.
Looking at me.
But your brother doesn't live with you, right?
No.
But he was there.
How do you know he was there, patientzero?
He came by and yelled at me.
He knew I went to the field.
How did he know that?
I went by his house and took the shovel out of his shed before I went.
I guess he heard me.
He knew where I was going after that.
You said he yelled at you when you returned?
Yeah. He said he knew I was drunk and I took the truck to the field.
He said I was being a dumb fuck.
I shook my head and he threw a bottle at me.
I ducked, and he looked at me with those same dull eyes he had earlier in the kitchen.
They looked like those empty sockets.
I went in and locked the door and he stood out there stark still for a good hour before he left.
Please, let me know your name. I will help you.
I am worried about you, patientzero.
Fucking kidding me?
I'm nobody. I am tiny black letters on a screen to you.
You sit there, I'd imagine, in your office, with your hardwood floors and your decorative trinkets and fake flowers on the desk.
Your husband gets home and kisses your cheek as you wave him off because you are busy with a client.
Dinner is in the refrigerator, you say to him over your shoulder.
And you think, sitting there all prim and proper, that you could somehow help a poor sick bastard like me.
You don't fucking know me, Hortence.
You know NOTHING.
Then tell me, patientzero.
Tell me your name so I may get to know you.
Call me Ishmael.
Moby-Dick, right?
I like to read sometimes.
Do you have a friend or a trusted relative you could call?
Yeah, I could call Joe Blow.
Hello, Joe? I killed a lady and left her in a field to rot.
How about you come over and drink with me 'til my brother blows my brains out to cover up the stupid shit we did?
That's not quite what I had in mind.
I know. I'm sorry.
I don't know what's wrong with me.
I feel guilty about being mean to you.
To be honest, I don't have any friends.
Why do you think that is?
My brother was the bad boy who got all the pretty girls.
I was the kid with his nose buried in a book.
We've both got our problems.
Does your brother have friends?
Not anymore, no.
How come?
He beat a guy bloody his senior year of high school.
No one came near him after that.
But you did?
I knew why he did it.
Why?
Something the kid said to him.
He said his uncle fucked our mom before she left us, and that our dad was too spineless to keep her.
He said our mom was a slut.
And he said my brother was going to end up just like my dad.
It's a sore spot for my brother.
I'd think so. That's terrible.
Yeah. He got a lot worse after that.
But no one knew why he assaulted that boy.
He was too ashamed to tell, and the kid was too afraid.
People talked, and they said it was because my brother was jealous of the kid's girlfriend.
But he told me the truth.
None of it matters now, though.
How come?
Because the lady is seeking revenge.
I hear her singing.
You hear her now?
Yeah.
What is she singing?
He will come for you soon, by the light of the moon.
He will come for you soon.
I need to know your name. Please.
He's going to kill me.
I will help you.
Let me in.
I did. I told you all of it.
Except your name.
Look, this refrain is getting old.
Why did you seek out therapy? Be honest with me.
I liked the thought of speaking to someone freely, of unburdening myself.
And I'd hoped you'd tell me how to get rid of the guilt, too.
There's not a prescription for curing guilt. We work at it, together.
I'm right here with you.
But I have immediate concerns about your safety and I am required to address those.
You are concerned about my brother, not about me.
I am concerned about both of you.
And round and round we go.
patientzero is disconnected.
Please, when you receive this message, call me at the number on my profile page. I need to speak with you.
Stay safe.
Dr. Took is disconnected.

patientzero is connected.
Dr. Took.
I found her.
The lady we killed.
I looked for her online and found a warrant out for her arrest.
She'd been involved in some insurance fraud or something, I guess.
She's not from around here, of course.
They found her car and towed it, but I guess they thought she'd ran off.
I think they gave up looking, myself.
There's an old mugshot of her online.
Her eyes looked empty even then.
